### 2. Sass Directory Structure (The 7-1 Pattern)

Using a clean CSS structure ensures the style system scales well as we add layouts, dashboard metrics, and interactive components. We recommend using a modular Sass architecture:

```text
/frontend/scss/
├── /abstracts/
│   ├── _variables.scss   # Colors ($brand-red, $bg-light), typography
│   └── _mixins.scss      # Media queries, flex/grid helpers
├── /base/
│   ├── _reset.scss       # Default browser resets
│   └── _typography.scss  # Google Fonts import (Inter) and global font-sizes
├── /components/
│   ├── _buttons.scss     # Portal access button, push active, finalize
│   ├── _tables.scss      # Table layouts, row hover styles, cell spacing
│   ├── _forms.scss       # Card selects, textareas, inputs
│   └── _toast.scss       # Fixed bottom-right toast message alerts
├── /layout/
│   ├── _header.scss      # Brand bar with slanted logo clip-path
│   ├── _navbar.scss      # Role-based dynamic navigation list
│   └── _shell.scss       # h-screen overflow-hidden base dashboard container
├── /pages/
│   ├── _auth.scss        # Fullscreen login view with backdrop Unsplash image
│   ├── _dashboard.scss   # Metric analytics layout
│   └── _tv.scss          # Dark theme live monitor display layout
└── main.scss             # Primary compiler node that @imports all of the above
```

*In `main.scss` compilation compile output to `/frontend/css/main.css` for integration in HTML head.*

